[src:biofuel/2019-in-climate-change] This article documents events, research findings, scientific and technological advances, and human actions to measure, predict, mitigate, and adapt to the effects of global warming and climate change—during the year 2019.
[src:biofuel/2019-in-climate-change] National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA).
[src:biofuel/2020-in-climate-change] This article documents events, research findings, scientific and technological advances, and human actions to measure, predict, mitigate, and adapt to the effects of global warming and climate change—during the year 2020.
[src:biofuel/2021-in-climate-change] This article documents events, research findings, scientific and technological advances, and human actions to measure, predict, mitigate, and adapt to the effects of global warming and climate change—during the year 2021.
[src:biofuel/2021-in-climate-change] among climate experts (2010–2015) reflect that the level of scientific consensus correlates with expertise in climate science.
[src:biofuel/2021-in-climate-change] and a 2021 study concluded that consensus exceeded 99%.
[src:biofuel/2021-in-climate-change] Another 2021 study found that 98.7% of climate experts indicated that the Earth is getting warmer mostly because of human activity.
[src:biofuel/2022-in-climate-change] This article documents events, research findings, scientific and technological advances, and human actions to measure, predict, mitigate, and adapt to the effects of global warming and climate change—during the year 2022.
[src:biofuel/2022-in-climate-change] A 2022 study found that the public substantially underestimates the degree of scientific consensus that humans are causing climate change.
[src:biofuel/2022-in-climate-change] found scientific consensus to range from 98.7–100%.
[src:biofuel/2022-in-climate-change] Research found that 80–90% of Americans underestimate the prevalence of support for major climate change mitigation policies and climate concern.
[src:biofuel/2022-in-climate-change] While 66–80% Americans support these policies, Americans estimate the prevalence to be 37–43%.
[src:biofuel/2022-in-climate-change] National political divides on the seriousness of climate change consistently correlate with political ideology, with right-wing opinion being more negative.
[src:biofuel/2023-in-climate-change] This article documents events, research findings, scientific and technological advances, and human actions to measure, predict, mitigate, and adapt to the effects of global warming and climate change—during the year 2023.
[src:biofuel/2024-in-climate-change] This article documents events, research findings, scientific and technological advances, and human actions to measure, predict, mitigate, and adapt to the effects of global warming and climate change—during the year 2024.
[src:biofuel/2024-in-climate-change] paper to conclude that climate change's increase of water temperatures intensified peak wind speeds in all eleven 2024 Atlantic hurricanes.
[src:biofuel/2024-in-climate-change] Scientists in the field of extreme event attribution have concluded that in virtually all countries and territories around the world in a year-long period beginning in May 2024, human-caused global warming has increased the number of days of extreme heat events over long-term norms.
[src:biofuel/2024-in-climate-change] As a source of electric power in the EU, renewables overtook fossil fuels by 2020, and solar and wind together exceeded fossil fuels by 2025.
[src:biofuel/2024-in-climate-change] The share of electricity coming from renewable sources continues to vary widely among European nations.
[src:biofuel/2024-in-climate-change] A few countries generate more electricity from renewables than is consumed in total.
[src:biofuel/2025-in-climate-change-p01] This article documents notable events, research findings, scientific and technological advances, and human actions to measure, predict, mitigate, and adapt to the effects of global warming and climate change—during the year 2025.
[src:biofuel/2025-in-climate-change-p01] reached a new all-time minimum in early February, and remained below the previous record of February 2023 for the rest of the month.
[src:biofuel/2025-in-climate-change-p01] (Earth's responsiveness to increases in greenhouse gas concentrations).
[src:biofuel/2025-in-climate-change-p01] , regulation of aerosols improved air quality, but aerosols' cooling effect became inadequate to temper the increasing warming effect of greenhouse gases—explaining unexpectedly large global warming in 2023-2024.
[src:biofuel/2025-in-climate-change-p01] have concluded that in virtually all countries and territories around the world in a one-year period beginning in May 2024, human-caused global warming has increased the number of days of extreme heat events over long-term norms.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] In general, biofuels emit fewer greenhouse gas emissions when burned in an engine and are generally considered carbon-neutral fuels as the carbon emitted has been captured from the atmosphere by the crops used in production.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] However, life-cycle assessments of biofuels have shown large emissions associated with the potential land-use change required to produce additional biofuel feedstocks.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] The outcomes of lifecycle assessments (LCAs) for biofuels are highly situational and dependent on many factors including the type of feedstock, production routes, data variations, and methodological choices.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Estimates about the climate impact from biofuels vary widely based on the methodology and exact situation examined.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Therefore, the climate change mitigation potential of biofuel varies considerably: in some scenarios biofuel emission levels are comparable to fossil fuels, and in other scenarios the use of biofuel results in negative emissions.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Global demand for biofuels is predicted to increase by 56% over 2022–2027.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] By 2027 worldwide biofuel production is expected to supply 5.4% of the world's fuels for transport including 1% of aviation fuel.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Demand for aviation biofuel is forecast to increase.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] However some policy has been criticised for favoring ground transportation over aviation.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] The IEA says that biofuel should particularly be used for applications which are difficult to electrify, such as shipping and aviation.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] The two most common types of biofuel are bioethanol and biodiesel.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] The United States is the largest producer of bioethanol, while the EU is the largest producer of biodiesel.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Meanwhile, Brazil produces and uses large amounts of bioethanol in vehicles, including in some flex-fuel cars exclusively available in Brazil.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] The energy content in the global production of bioethanol and biodiesel is 2.2 and 1.8 EJ per year, respectively.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] The term *biofuel* is used in different ways.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] One definition is "Biofuels are biobased products, in solid, liquid, or gaseous forms.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Other publications reserve the term biofuel for *liquid* or *gaseous* fuels, used for transportation.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] The IPCC Sixth Assessment Report defines *biofuel* as "A fuel, generally in liquid form, produced from biomass.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Biofuels include bioethanol from sugarcane, sugar beet or maize, and biodiesel from canola or soybeans.".
[src:biofuel/biofuel] It goes on to define *biomass* in this context as "organic material excluding the material that is fossilized or embedded in geological formations".
[src:biofuel/biofuel] This means that coal or other fossil fuels is not a form of biomass in this context.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Bioethanol is an alcohol made by fermentation, mostly from carbohydrates produced in sugar or starch crops such as maize, sugarcane, or sweet sorghum.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Cellulosic biomass, derived from non-food sources, such as trees and grasses, is also being developed as a feedstock for ethanol production.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Ethanol can be used as a fuel for vehicles in its pure form (E100), but it is usually used as a gasoline additive to increase octane ratings and improve vehicle emissions.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Biodiesel is produced from oils or fats using transesterification.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] It can be used as a fuel for vehicles in its pure form (B100), but it is usually used as a diesel additive to reduce levels of particulates, carbon monoxide, and hydrocarbons from diesel-powered vehicles.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] To avoid a "food versus fuel" dilemma, second-generation biofuels and third-generation biofuels (also called advanced biofuels or sustainable biofuels or drop-in biofuels) are made from feedstocks which do not directly compete with food or feed crop such as waste products and energy crops.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] The feedstock used to make the fuels either grow on arable land but are byproducts of the main crop, or they are grown on marginal land.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Second-generation feedstocks also include straw, bagasse, perennial grasses, jatropha, waste vegetable oil, municipal solid waste and so forth.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Biologically produced alcohols, most commonly ethanol, and less commonly propanol and butanol, are produced by the action of microorganisms and enzymes through the fermentation of sugars or starches (easiest to produce) or cellulose (more difficult to produce).
[src:biofuel/biofuel] The IEA estimates that ethanol production used 20% of sugar supplies and 13% of corn supplies in 2021.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Ethanol fuel is the most common biofuel worldwide, particularly in Brazil.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Alcohol fuels are produced by fermentation of sugars derived from wheat, corn, sugar beets, sugar cane, molasses and any sugar or starch from which alcoholic beverages such as whiskey, can be made (such as potato and fruit waste, etc.).
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Production methods used are enzyme digestion (to release sugars from stored starches), fermentation of the sugars, distillation and drying.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] The distillation process requires significant energy input to generate heat.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Heat is sometimes generated with unsustainable natural gas fossil fuel, but cellulosic biomass such as bagasse is the most common fuel in Brazil, while pellets, wood chips and also waste heat are more common in Europe.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Corn-to-ethanol and other food stocks has led to the development of cellulosic ethanol.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Ethanol fuel can be combined with gasoline to create a more environmentally friendly fuel though there are more viable substitutions to gasoline such as Butanol.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Methanol is currently produced from natural gas, a non-renewable fossil fuel.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] In the future it is hoped to be produced from biomass as biomethanol.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] This is technically feasible, but the production is currently being postponed for concerns that the economic viability is still pending.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] The methanol economy is an alternative to the hydrogen economy to be contrasted with today's hydrogen production from natural gas.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Butanol (C 4H 9OH) is formed by ABE fermentation (acetone, butanol, ethanol) and experimental modifications of the process show potentially high net energy gains with biobutanol as the only liquid product.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] *Escherichia coli* strains have also been successfully engineered to produce butanol by modifying their amino acid metabolism.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] One drawback to butanol production in *E. coli* remains the high cost of nutrient rich media, however, recent work has demonstrated *E. coli* can produce butanol with minimal nutritional supplementation.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Biobutanol is sometimes called biogasoline, which is incorrect as it is chemically different, being an alcohol and not a hydrocarbon like gasoline.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Biodiesel is the most common biofuel in Europe.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] It is produced from oils or fats using transesterification and is a liquid similar in composition to fossil/mineral diesel.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Chemically, it consists mostly of fatty acid methyl (or ethyl) esters (FAMEs).
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Feedstocks for biodiesel include animal fats, vegetable oils, soy, rapeseed, jatropha, mahua, mustard, flax, sunflower, palm oil, hemp, field pennycress, *Pongamia pinnata* and algae.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Pure biodiesel (B100, also known as "neat" biodiesel) currently reduces emissions with up to 60% compared to diesel Second generation B100.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] As of 2020, researchers at Australia's CSIRO have been studying safflower oil as an engine lubricant, and researchers at Montana State University's Advanced Fuels Center in the US have been studying the oil's performance in a large diesel engine, with results described as a "breakthrough".
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Biodiesel can be used in any diesel engine and modified equipment when mixed with mineral diesel.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] It can also be used in its pure form (B100) in diesel engines, but some maintenance and performance problems may occur during wintertime utilization, since the fuel becomes somewhat more viscous at lower temperatures, depending on the feedstock used.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Electronically controlled 'common rail' and 'Unit Injector' type systems from the late 1990s onwards can only use biodiesel blended with conventional diesel fuel.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] These engines have finely metered and atomized multiple-stage injection systems that are very sensitive to the viscosity of the fuel.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Many current-generation diesel engines are designed to run on B100 without altering the engine itself, although this depends on the fuel rail design.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Since biodiesel is an effective solvent and cleans residues deposited by mineral diesel, engine filters may need to be replaced more often, as the biofuel dissolves old deposits in the fuel tank and pipes.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] It also effectively cleans the engine combustion chamber of carbon deposits, helping to maintain efficiency.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Biodiesel is an oxygenated fuel, meaning it contains a reduced amount of carbon and higher hydrogen and oxygen content than fossil diesel.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] This improves the combustion of biodiesel and reduces the particulate emissions from unburnt carbon.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] However, using pure biodiesel may increase NOx-emissions Biodiesel is also safe to handle and transport because it is non-toxic and biodegradable, and has a high flash point of about 300 °F (148 °C) compared to petroleum diesel fuel, which has a flash point of 125 °F (52 °C).
[src:biofuel/biofuel] In many European countries, a 5% biodiesel blend is widely used and is available at thousands of gas stations.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] In France, biodiesel is incorporated at a rate of 8% in the fuel used by all French diesel vehicles.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Avril Group produces under the brand Diester, a fifth of 11 million tons of biodiesel consumed annually by the European Union.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] It is the leading European producer of biodiesel.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Green diesel can be produced from a combination of biochemical and thermochemical processes.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Conventional green diesel is produced through hydroprocessing biological oil feedstocks, such as vegetable oils and animal fats.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Recently, it is produced using series of thermochemical processes such as pyrolysis and hydroprocessing.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] In the thermochemical route, syngas produced from gasification, bio-oil produced from pyrolysis or biocrude produced from hydrothermal liquefaction is upgraded to green diesel using hydroprocessing.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Hydroprocessing is the process of using hydrogen to reform a molecular structure.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] For example, hydrocracking which is a widely used hydroprocessing technique in refineries is used at elevated temperatures and pressure in the presence of a catalyst to break down larger molecules, such as those found in vegetable oils, into shorter hydrocarbon chains used in diesel engines.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Green diesel may also be called renewable diesel, drop-in biodiesel, hydrotreated vegetable oil (HVO fuel) or hydrogen-derived renewable diesel.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Unlike biodiesel, green diesel has exactly the same chemical properties as petroleum-based diesel.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] It does not require new engines, pipelines or infrastructure to distribute and use, but has not been produced at a cost that is competitive with petroleum.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Gasoline versions are also being developed.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Green diesel is being developed in Louisiana and Singapore by ConocoPhillips, Neste Oil, Valero, Dynamic Fuels, and Honeywell UOP as well as Preem in Gothenburg, Sweden, creating what is known as Evolution Diesel.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Straight unmodified edible vegetable oil is generally not used as fuel, but lower-quality oil has been used for this purpose.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Used vegetable oil is increasingly being processed into biodiesel, or (more rarely) cleaned of water and particulates and then used as a fuel.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] The IEA estimates that biodiesel production used 17% of global vegetable oil supplies in 2021.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Oils and fats reacted with 10 pounds of a short-chain alcohol (usually methanol) in the presence of a catalyst (usually sodium hydroxide [NaOH] can be hydrogenated to give a diesel substitute.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] The resulting product is a straight-chain hydrocarbon with a high cetane number, low in aromatics and sulfur and does not contain oxygen.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Hydrogenated oils can be blended with diesel in all proportions.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] They have several advantages over biodiesel, including good performance at low temperatures, no storage stability problems and no susceptibility to microbial attack.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Biogasoline can be produced biologically and thermochemically.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] The enzymes converted the sugar into fatty acids and then turned these into hydrocarbons that were chemically and structurally identical to those found in commercial gasoline fuel.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] The thermochemical approach of producing biogasoline are similar to those used to produce biodiesel.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Biogasoline may also be called drop-in gasoline or renewable gasoline.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Bioethers (also referred to as fuel ethers or oxygenated fuels) are cost-effective compounds that act as octane rating enhancers.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] "Bioethers are produced by the reaction of reactive iso-olefins, such as iso-butylene, with bioethanol." Bioethers are created from wheat or sugar beets, and also be produced from the waste glycerol that results from the production of biodiesel.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] They also enhance engine performance, while significantly reducing engine wear and toxic exhaust emissions.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] By greatly reducing the amount of ground-level ozone emissions, they contribute to improved air quality.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] In transportation fuel there are six ether additives: dimethyl ether (DME), diethyl ether (DEE), methyl *tert*-butyl ether (MTBE), ethyl *tert*-butyl ether (ETBE), *tert*-amyl methyl ether (TAME), and *tert*-amyl ethyl ether (TAEE).
[src:biofuel/biofuel] The European Fuel Oxygenates Association identifies MTBE and ETBE as the most commonly used ethers in fuel to replace lead.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Ethers were introduced in Europe in the 1970s to replace the highly toxic compound.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Although Europeans still use bioether additives, the U.S.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Energy Policy Act of 2005 lifted a requirement for reformulated gasoline to include an oxygenate, leading to less MTBE being added to fuel.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Although bioethers are likely to replace ethers produced from petroleum in the UK, it is highly unlikely they will become a fuel in and of itself due to the low energy density.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] An aviation biofuel (also known as bio-jet fuel, sustainable aviation fuel (SAF), or bio-aviation fuel (BAF)) is a biofuel used to power aircraft.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] The International Air Transport Association (IATA) considers it a key element in reducing the environmental impact of aviation.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Aviation biofuel is used to decarbonize medium and long-haul air travel.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] These types of travel generate the most emissions.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Synthetic paraffinic kerosene (SPK) refers to any non-petroleum-based fuel designed to replace kerosene jet fuel, which is often, but not always, made from biomass.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Biofuels are biomass-derived fuels from plants, animals, or waste; depending on which type of biomass is used, they could lower CO2 emissions by 20–98% compared to conventional jet fuel.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] The first test flight using blended biofuel was in 2008, and in 2011, blended fuels with 50% biofuels were allowed on commercial flights.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] In 2023 SAF production was 600 million liters, representing 0.2% of global jet fuel use.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] By 2024, SAF production was to increase to 1.3 billion liters (1 million tonnes), representing 0.3% of global jet fuel consumption and 11% of global renewable fuel production.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] This increase came as major US production facilities delayed their ramp-up until 2025, having initially been expected to reach 1.9 billion liters.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Small piston engines can be modified to burn ethanol.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Sustainable biofuels are an alternative to electrofuels.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Sustainable aviation fuel is certified as being sustainable by a third-party organisation.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] SAF technology faces significant challenges due to feedstock constraints.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] The oils and fats known as hydrotreated esters and fatty acids (Hefa), crucial for SAF production, are in limited supply as demand increases.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Although advanced e-fuels technology, which combines waste CO2 with clean hydrogen, presents a promising solution, it is still under development and comes with high costs.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] To overcome these issues, SAF developers are exploring more readily available feedstocks such as woody biomass and agricultural and municipal waste, aiming to produce lower-carbon jet fuel more sustainably and efficiently.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Biogas is a mixture composed primarily of methane and carbon dioxide produced by the process of anaerobic digestion of organic material by micro-organisms.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Other trace components of this mixture includes water vapor, hydrogen sulfide, siloxanes, hydrocarbons, ammonia, oxygen, carbon monoxide, and nitrogen.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] It can be produced either from biodegradable waste materials or by the use of energy crops fed into anaerobic digesters to supplement gas yields.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] The solid byproduct, digestate, can be used as a biofuel or a fertilizer.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] When CO2 and other impurities are removed from biogas, it is called biomethane.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] The CO2 can also be combined with hydrogen in methanation to form more methane.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Biogas can be recovered from mechanical biological treatment waste processing systems.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Landfill gas, a less clean form of biogas, is produced in landfills through naturally occurring anaerobic digestion.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] If it escapes into the atmosphere, it acts as a greenhouse gas.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] In Sweden, "waste-to-energy" power plants capture methane biogas from garbage and use it to power transport systems.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Farmers can produce biogas from cattle manure via anaerobic digesters.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Syngas, a mixture of carbon monoxide, hydrogen and various hydrocarbons, is produced by partial combustion of biomass (combustion with an amount of oxygen that is not sufficient to convert the biomass completely to carbon dioxide and water).
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Before partial combustion the biomass is dried and sometimes pyrolysed.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Syngas is more efficient than direct combustion of the original biofuel; more of the energy contained in the fuel is extracted.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Syngas may be burned directly in internal combustion engines, turbines or high-temperature fuel cells.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] The wood gas generator, a wood-fueled gasification reactor, can be connected to an internal combustion engine.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Syngas can be used to produce methanol, dimethyl ether and hydrogen, or converted via the Fischer–Tropsch process to produce a diesel substitute, or a mixture of alcohols that can be blended into gasoline.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Gasification normally relies on temperatures greater than 700 °C.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Lower-temperature gasification is desirable when co-producing biochar, but results in syngas polluted with tar.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] The term "biofuels" is also used for solid fuels that are made from biomass, even though this is less common.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Algae can be produced in ponds or tanks on land, and out at sea.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Algal fuels have high yields, a high ignition point, can be grown with minimal impact on fresh water resources, can be produced using saline water and wastewater, and are biodegradable and relatively harmless to the environment if spilled.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] However, production requires large amounts of energy and fertilizer, the produced fuel degrades faster than other biofuels, and it does not flow well in cold temperatures.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] By 2017, due to economic considerations, most efforts to produce fuel from algae have been abandoned or changed to other applications.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Third and fourth-generation biofuels also include biofuels that are produced by bioengineered organisms i.e. algae and cyanobacteria.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Algae and cyanobacteria will use water, carbon dioxide, and solar energy to produce biofuels.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] This method of biofuel production is still at the research level.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] The biofuels that are secreted by the bioengineered organisms are expected to have higher photon-to-fuel conversion efficiency, compared to older generations of biofuels.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] One of the advantages of this class of biofuels is that the cultivation of the organisms that produce the biofuels does not require the use of arable land.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] The disadvantages include the cost of cultivating the biofuel-producing organisms being very high.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Also, current methods of using algae often have worse environmental impacts than using other crops.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Recent research highlights that the transition to sustainable energy is reliant on the widespread adoption of third- and fourth-generation biofuels, which utilize non-food sources such as algae and incorporate advanced processes like artificial photosynthesis.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] These alternatives are essential for climate change mitigation because they significantly reduce the land-use competition and sustainability risks associated with earlier biofuel generations.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Electrofuels and solar fuels may or may not be biofuels, depending on whether they contain biological elements.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Electrofuels are made by storing electrical energy in the chemical bonds of liquids and gases.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] The primary targets are butanol, biodiesel, and hydrogen, but include other alcohols and carbon-containing gases such as methane and butane.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] A solar fuel is a synthetic chemical fuel produced from solar energy.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Light is converted to chemical energy, typically by reducing protons to hydrogen, or carbon dioxide to organic compounds.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] A bio-digester is a mechanized toilet that uses decomposition and sedimentation to turn human waste into a renewable fuel called biogas.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Biogas can be made from substances like agricultural waste and sewage.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] The bio-digester uses a process called anaerobic digestion to produce biogas.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Anaerobic digestion uses a chemical process to break down organic matter with the use of microorganisms in the absence of oxygen to produce biogas.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] The processes involved in anaerobic respiration are hydrolysis, acidogenesis, acetogenesis, and methanogenesis.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Global biofuel production was 81 Mtoe in 2017 which represented an annual increase of about 3% compared to 2010.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] In 2017, the US was the largest biofuel producer in the world producing 37 Mtoe, followed by Brazil and South America at 23 Mtoe and Europe (mainly Germany) at 12 Mtoe.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] An assessment from 2017 found that: "Biofuels will never be a major transport fuel as there is just not enough land in the world to grow plants to make biofuel for all vehicles.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] In 2021, worldwide biofuel production provided 4.3% of the world's fuels for transport, including a very small amount of aviation biofuel.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] By 2027, worldwide biofuel production is expected to supply 5.4% of the world's fuels for transport including 1% of aviation fuel.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] The US, Europe, Brazil and Indonesia are driving the majority of biofuel consumption growth.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] This demand for biodiesel, renewable diesel and biojet fuel is projected to increase by 44% (21 billion litres) over 2022-2027.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Issues relating to biofuel are social, economic, environmental and technical problems that may arise from biofuel production and use.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Social and economic issues include the "food vs fuel" debate and the need to develop responsible policies and economic instruments to ensure sustainable biofuel production.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Farming for biofuels feedstock can be detrimental to the environment if not done sustainably.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Environmental concerns include deforestation, biodiversity loss and soil erosion as a result of land clearing for biofuels agriculture.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] While biofuels can contribute to reduction in global carbon emissions, indirect land use change for biofuel production can have the inverse effect.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Technical issues include possible modifications necessary to run the engine on biofuel, as well as energy balance and efficiency.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] The International Resource Panel outlined the wider and interrelated factors that need to be considered when deciding on the relative merits of pursuing one biofuel over another.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] The IRP concluded that not all biofuels perform equally in terms of their effect on climate, energy security and ecosystems, and suggested that environmental and social effects need to be assessed throughout the entire life-cycle.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] In general, biofuels emit fewer greenhouse gas emissions when burned in an engine and are generally considered carbon-neutral fuels as the carbon they emit has been captured from the atmosphere by the crops used in biofuel production.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] They can have greenhouse gas emissions ranging from as low as -127.1 gCO2eq per MJ when carbon capture is incorporated into their production to those exceeding 95 gCO2eq per MJ when land-use change is significant.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Several factors are responsible for the variation in emission numbers of biofuel, such as feedstock and its origin, fuel production technique, system boundary definitions, and energy sources.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] However, many government policies, such as those by the European Union and the UK, require that biofuels have at least 65% greenhouse gas emissions savings (or 70% if it is renewable fuels of non-biological origins) relative to fossil fuels.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Life-cycle assessments of first-generation biofuels have shown large emissions associated with the potential land-use change required to produce additional biofuel feedstocks.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] If no land-use change is involved, first-generation biofuels can—on average—have lower emissions than fossil fuels.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] However, biofuel production can compete with food crop production.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Up to 40% of corn produced in the United States is used to make ethanol and worldwide 10% of all grain is turned into biofuel.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] A 50% reduction in grain used for biofuels in the US and Europe would replace all of Ukraine's grain exports.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Several studies have shown that reductions in emissions from biofuels are achieved at the expense of other impacts, such as acidification, eutrophication, water footprint and biodiversity loss.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Second-generation biofuels are thought to increase environmental sustainability since the non-food part of plants is being used to produce second-generation biofuels instead of being disposed of.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] But the use of second-generation biofuels increases the competition for lignocellulosic biomass, increasing the cost of these biofuels.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] In theory, third-generation biofuels, produced from algae, shouldn't harm the environment more than first- or second-generation biofuels due to lower changes in land use and the fact that they do not require pesticide use for production.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] When looking at the data however, it has been shown that the environmental cost to produce the infrastructure and energy required for third generation biofuel production, are higher than the benefits provided from the biofuels use.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] The European Commission has officially approved a measure to phase out palm oil-based biofuels by 2030.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Unsustainable palm oil agriculture has caused significant environmental and social problems, including deforestation and pollution.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] The production of biofuels can be very energy intensive, which, if generated from non-renewable sources, can heavily mitigate the benefits gained through biofuel use.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] A solution proposed to solve this issue is to supply biofuel production facilities with excess nuclear energy, which can supplement the power provided by fossil fuels.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] This can provide a carbon inexpensive solution to help reduce the environmental impacts of biofuel production.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] As farmers worldwide respond to higher crop prices in order to maintain the global food supply-and-demand balance, pristine lands are cleared to replace the food crops that were diverted elsewhere to biofuels' production.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Because natural lands, such as rainforests and grasslands, store carbon in their soil and biomass as plants grow each year, clearance of wilderness for new farms translates to a net increase in greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Due to this off-site change in the carbon stock of the soil and the biomass, indirect land use change has consequences in the greenhouse gas (GHG) balance of a biofuel.
[src:biofuel/biofuel] Other authors have also argued that indirect land use changes produce other significant social and environmental impacts, affecting biodiversity, water quality, food prices and supply, land tenure, worker migration, and community and cultural stability.
